          Washington Leads the Nation in Retail Theft: What It Means for Stores Across the Puget Sound
        </h1>
        <div class="flex items-center text-lg mb-8">
          <time datetime="2026-03-30">March 30, 2026</time>
          <span class="mx-4">&bull;</span>
          <span>12 min read</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed">
          A Forbes Advisor analysis ranked Washington <strong>first in the nation</strong> for retail theft impact. Fred Meyer is closing six stores across western Washington, citing theft and regulatory costs. King County prosecutors charged <strong>640 felony retail crime cases in 2025</strong> &mdash; the highest in five years. In Lynnwood, shoplifting arrests have risen 666% since 2015. The state legislature is weighing 11 organized retail crime proposals. And the stores that remain open are left wondering what happens next.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Quick Answer Section -->
    <QuickAnswer
      question="How bad is retail theft in Washington state compared to the rest of the country?"
      answer="Washington ranks #1 nationally for retail theft impact according to Forbes Advisor, with 48% more reported retail thefts than expected based on population. The state loses roughly $2.7 billion annually to retail theft, translating to $603 million in missed state and local tax revenue. King County prosecutors filed 640 felony economic and property crime cases in 2025, a five-year high. Fred Meyer is closing six stores across western Washington, and Rite Aid closed 27 Washington locations in September 2025. The state legislature is considering 11 organized retail crime proposals, and the Attorney General's Organized Retail Crime Unit has secured its first convictions. Mobile surveillance in retail parking lots has been shown to reduce property crime by up to 51% according to meta-analysis research."
    />

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <section class="py-16">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-6 max-w-4xl">
        <div class="blog-content prose prose-lg max-w-none">

          <!-- Stats Section -->
          <div class="mb-12">
            <StatBox
              layout="grid"
              stats={[
                {
                  value: "#1",
                  label: "Washington's national ranking for retail theft impact",
